Files:
- plugins/outlook/src/tools/download-attachment.ts (triggerBrowserDownload function, lines 22-38)

Context:
Current triggerBrowserDownload (lines 22-38):
  function triggerBrowserDownload(bytes: Uint8Array, filename: string, mimeType: string): void {
    const buffer = new ArrayBuffer(bytes.byteLength);
    new Uint8Array(buffer).set(bytes);
    const blob = new Blob([buffer], { type: mimeType });
    const url = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
    const a = document.createElement('a');
    a.href = url;
    a.download = filename;
    a.style.display = 'none';
    document.body.appendChild(a);
    a.click();
    // Cleanup after a short delay to ensure the download starts
    setTimeout(() => {
      document.body.removeChild(a);
      URL.revokeObjectURL(url);
    }, 1000);
  }

Fix:
  function triggerBrowserDownload(bytes: Uint8Array, filename: string, mimeType: string): void {
    const buffer = new ArrayBuffer(bytes.byteLength);
    new Uint8Array(buffer).set(bytes);
    const blob = new Blob([buffer], { type: mimeType });
    const url = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
    const a = document.createElement('a');
    a.href = url;
    a.download = filename;
    a.style.display = 'none';
    document.body.appendChild(a);
    a.click();
    document.body.removeChild(a);
    URL.revokeObjectURL(url);
  }

Modern browsers (Chrome 60+) start the download when click() is called and do not need the blob URL to remain valid after that point. The 1-second delay was a historical workaround for older browsers.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the Blob construction or ArrayBuffer setup
- Do NOT add a requestAnimationFrame or any async delay — synchronous cleanup is correct
